 A pension scheme is basically a plan for how much money you get when you retire. Pension schemes are run by companies and are usually funded by the employees' own contributions and the money they earn. When you retire, the pension scheme pays you out based on the amount of money you've contributed over your working life. The mortgage is the debt you owe the bank, and the deposit is the amount of money you've put down as a guarantee that you'll pay the mortgage back. The amount of the deposit is limited by how much you can afford to pay, and the amount of the mortgage is limited by how much you can afford to pay. If you want to pay a lot of money back, you have to put down a lot of money as a deposit. It's the same with pension schemes. If you want to pay out a lot of money when you retire, you have to contribute a lot of money to the pension scheme. I think you're asking for an explanation of why we say a line has one dimension while a point has none, and why we say a point has zero dimensions. This is a fundamental concept in geometry and math. A line has one dimension because it's a one-dimensional object, meaning it has only one length or direction. This is because a line is a set of points that are all connected by a straight line. All of the points on a line have the same length and the same direction, which is why we say a line has one dimension.

A point, on the other hand, has zero dimensions because it is a single point and it doesn't have any length or direction. It's just a single location in space. A point is not connected to any other point, so it doesn't have any length or direction.

So, to answer your question, a line has one dimension because it's a set of connected points, and a point has zero dimensions because it's a single, isolated point.

How does NAT ( Network Address Translation ) work. I've googled it and all the answers are very complex. I need it explained to me like I'm five. Thanks! Explain like I'm five.assistant

So, when you're on the internet, you can have a lot of computers on your network. But the internet only knows one address for each computer. So, it can only talk to one computer at a time. But, you can have a lot of computers on your network, so you need a way to make them talk to each other. That's where NAT comes in. It's like a special kind of translator. It says, hey, this computer is on your network, but I'll talk to it like it's on the internet. So, it makes the computer's address look like it's on the internet, even though it's not. Then, when the computer on the internet wants to talk to it, it says, hey, I know where that computer is, it's on your network. So, it sends the message to your computer, which then says, hey, I know where that computer is, it's on my network. And so on. It's like a big game of telephone.

 VAT is short for Value Added Tax, and GST is short for Goods and Services Tax. So, basically, both are taxes that are added to goods and services, and are used to fund government programs. They are used in many countries around the world, including Canada, the UK, and Australia. The tax rate is usually a percentage of the price of the goods and services being sold, and is added to the price before it is sold. For example, if a shirt is $10, a 10% VAT would be added to the price, making it $11. The GST is similar, but the tax rate may vary depending on the country and the type of goods and services being sold. For example, a 5% GST would be added to the price of a shirt, making it $10.50. The VAT and GST are used to fund government programs, such as infrastructure, healthcare, and education, as well as to provide revenue for the government. They are an important source of tax revenue for governments around the world, and are used to support a wide range of public services and programs. In some countries, the VAT and GST are also used to fund social programs, such as unemployment benefits and pension payments. Computers have a special way of understanding things called ASCII. ASCII stands for American Standard Code for Information Interchange. It's like a special alphabet for computers. The ASCII alphabet includes 26 letters and 10 digits from 0 to 9. It also includes some special symbols like the exclamation mark and the dollar sign. But, computers don't understand letters and numbers in the same way that humans do. They understand ASCII as a whole, and they can distinguish between the letter 'A' and the number 65 because they know that the letter 'A' is represented by the ASCII code 65.
